 Sussex |first= |date=July 31, 2019 |title=HRH The Duchess of Sussex Shares A New Smart Works Initiative |url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/meghan-markle-smart-works-september-issue |magazine=Vogue |edition=British}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q3304418|c=Category:Meghan, Duchess of Sussex|the Duchess of Sussex|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|s=no|wikt=no|n=no|q=Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n* {{official website|https://sussexroyal.com/}}\n* [https://www.royal.uk/duchess-sussex The Duchess of Sussex] at the official website of the British royal family\n* [https://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/duke-and-duchess-sussex The Duke and Duchess of Sussex profile] at the official website of the [[Prince of Wales]]\n* {{IMDb name|1620783|Meghan Markle}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|The Duchess of Cambridge]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United Kingdom order of precedence|Ladies]]<br /> '''''The Duchess of Sussex''''' }}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Autumn Phillips]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{British princesses by marriage}}\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Ladies)}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Royalty|United Kingdom|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n[[Category:Meghan, Duchess of Sussex| ]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Immaculate Heart High School, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American Anglicans]]\n[[Category:American calligraphers]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American expatriate actresses in Canada]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:British baronesses|Kilkeel]]\n[[Category:British countesses|Dumbarton]]\n[[Category:British duchesses by marriage|Sussex]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism]]\n[[Category:Game show models]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Markle family|Meghan]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from View Park\u2013Windsor Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Wives of British princes]]\n[[Category:Women calligraphers]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic role:past tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meghan,_Duchess_of_Sussex"}
{"title_page": "Net force", "text_new": "Net force is the [[vector sum]] of forces acting on a particle or body. The net force is a single force that replaces the effect of the original forces on the particle's motion. It gives the particle the same [[acceleration]] as all those actual forces together as described by the [[Newton's laws of motion|Newton's second law of motion]].\n\nIn [[physics]], it is possible to determine the torquejhiapplication of a net force so that it maintains the movement of jets of the object under the original system of forces. Its associated torque, the net force, becomes the hi my dudes \nresultant force]]'' and has the same effect on the [[rotation]]al motion of the object as all actual forces taken together.<ref>Symon, Keith R. (1964), Mechanics, Addison-Wesley, {{LCCN|605164}}</ref>  It is possible for a system of forces to define a torque-free resultant force. In this case, the net force, when applied at the proper line of action, has the same effect on the body as all of the forces at their points of application. It is not always possible to find a torque-free resultant force.\n<!----\n  This discussion of forces on a particle and rigid body is confusing:\n\nA acting on an object may cause changes in the motion or in the shape (configuration) of the object. When two or more forces are acting on an object, the concepts of net force and resultant force are intended to simplify description of their effect on its motion.\n\nIf the forces are acting on a [[Part]] (the size of the object is so Tinsie Winnsie that it can be approximated by a point), they can only change its [[velocity]]. In that case, there is no difference between the net force and the resultant force because no rotation is associated with such objects.\n\nIf the object is an extended but [[rigid body]] (no change in shape), the forces can change its velocity (i.e. the velocity of its [[center of mass]], usually called its linear velocity) as well as its [[angular velocity]]. In that case, it may be useful to distinguish the resultant force from the net force. And even in the case of non-rigid objects (deformable bodies or systems), the concepts of net and resultant force are equally applicable to description of their overall motion.\n\nSome authors use \"resultant force\" and \"net force\" as synonyms, even when the forces act on extended bodies. However, this is generally not the case (see the note on usage at the end of the article) in [[mechanics]] and in those technical applications where full understanding and actual calculations of the rotating body [[dynamics (mechanics)|dynamics]] (or even of the [[static equilibrium]]) are required.\n ---->\n\n== Total force ==\n\n[[File:Addition of forces.JPG|thumb|350px|A<!--?: nother--> diagrammatic method for the addition of forces.]]\n\nForce is a [[Euclidean vector|vector]] quantity, which means that it has a magnitude and a direction, and it is usually denoted using boldface such as '''F''' or by using an arrow over the symbol, such as <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F</math>. \n\nGraphically, a force is represented as a line segment from its point of application ''A'' to a point ''B'', which defines its direction and magnitude.  The length of the segment ''AB'' represents the magnitude of the force.\n\n[[Vector calculus]] was developed in the late 1800s and early 1900s. The [[parallelogram rule]] used for the addition of forces, however, dates from antiquity and is noted explicitly by Galileo and Newton.<ref>Michael J. Crowe (1967). ''A History of Vector Analysis : The Evolution of the Idea of a Vectorial System''. Dover Publications (reprint edition; {{ISBN|0-486-67910-1}}).</ref> \n\nThe diagram shows the addition of the forces <math>\\scriptstyle  \\vec{F}_{1}</math> and <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{2}</math>. The sum <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F</math> of the two forces is drawn as the diagonal of a parallelogram defined by the two forces. \n<!----\n  This \"intuitive\" description is not intuitive:\n\nThis can be grasped intuitively: if the total force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F</math> should describe the joint effect of the two forces on a particle (which is the intrinsic meaning of addition), its direction should be closer to the direction of the stronger force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{2}</math>, and its amount should be greater than the amount of <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{2}</math> because <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{1}</math> also helps in pulling the particle in that  \"general\" direction (for the forces shown in the diagram). \n\nIndependent of this approximate intuitive judgment, the rule of parallelogram gives the exact result, which is easily verified by measuring the effects of the forces. The result can be approximately evaluated from the diagram or, based on the diagram, precisely calculated using elementary [[trigonometry]].\n ----><!----\n  This is not an alternative to the parallelogram rule, it -is- the parallelogram rule:\n\nInstead of using the parallelogram rule, the same result can be obtained by a simpler procedure (shown on the right side of the diagram). The line segments representing the original forces can be translated (in any order) so that one begins where the other ends. The same result for the vector sum is the line drawn from the beginning of the first segment to the end of the second&nbsp;\u2013 or to the end of the last one&nbsp;\u2013 which enables simple addition of more than two vectors. At the bottom of the diagram, this procedure is applied to the addition of two parallel and antiparallel forces, leading to the intuitively expected result: for parallel forces the amounts add up, whereas for the forces in opposite directions (antiparallel) the amount of the smaller force is subtracted from the bigger one.\n ---->\n\nForces applied to an extended body can have different points of application.  Forces are bound vectors and can be added only if they are applied at the same point.  The net force obtained from all the forces acting on a body  do not preserve its motion unless applied at the same point, and with the appropriate torque associated with the new point of application determined.  The net force on a body applied at a single point with the appropriate torque is known as the [[resultant force]] and torque.\n\n== Parallelogram rule for the addition of forces ==\n[[File:Parallelogram1.svg|right|Parallelogram ABCD]]\n\nA force is known as a bound vector\u2014which means it has a direction and magnitude and a point of application.  A convenient way to define a force is by a line segment from a point ''A'' to a point ''B''.  If we denote the coordinates of these points as '''A'''=(A<sub>x</sub>, A<sub>y</sub>, A<sub>z</sub>) and  '''B'''=(B<sub>x</sub>, B<sub>y</sub>, B<sub>z</sub>), then the force vector applied at ''A'' is given by\n: <math> \\mathbf{F}= \\mathbf{B}-\\mathbf{A} = (B_x-A_x, B_y-A_y, B_z-A_z). </math>\nThe length of the vector '''B'''-'''A''' defines the magnitude of '''F''' and is given by\n: <math> |\\mathbf{F}| = \\sqrt{(B_x-A_x)^2+(B_y-A_y)^2+(B_z-A_z)^2}. </math>\n\nThe sum of two forces '''F'''<sub>1</sub> and  '''F'''<sub>2</sub> applied at ''A'' can be computed from the sum of the segments that define them.  Let '''F'''<sub>1</sub>='''B'''-'''A''' and '''F'''<sub>2</sub>='''D'''-'''A''', then the sum of these two vectors is\n: <math> \\mathbf{F}=\\mathbf{F}_1+\\mathbf{F}_2 = \\mathbf{B}-\\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{D}-\\mathbf{A},</math>\nwhich can be written as\n: <math> \\mathbf{F}=\\mathbf{F}_1+\\mathbf{F}_2 = 2(\\frac{\\mathbf{B}+\\mathbf{D}}{2}-\\mathbf{A})=2(\\mathbf{E}-\\mathbf{A}),</math>\nwhere '''E''' is the midpoint of the segment '''BD''' that joins the points ''B'' and ''D''.  \n\nThus, the sum of the forces '''F'''<sub>1</sub> and '''F'''<sub>2</sub> is twice the segment joining ''A'' to the midpoint ''E'' of the segment joining the endpoints ''B'' and ''D'' of the two forces.  The doubling of this length is easily achieved by defining a segments '''BC''' and '''DC''' parallel to '''AD''' and '''AB''', respectively, to complete the parallelogram ''ABCD''.  The diagonal '''AC''' of this parallelogram is the sum of the two force vectors.  This is known as the parallelogram rule for the addition of forces.\n\n== Translation and rotation due to a force ==\n\n===Point forces===\nWhen a force acts on a particle, it is applied to a single point (the particle volume is negligible): this is a point force and the particle is its application point. But an external force on an extended body (object) can be applied to a number of its constituent particles, i.e. can be \"spread\" over some volume or surface of the body. However, determining its rotational effect on the body requires that we specify its point of application (actually, the line of application, as explained below). The problem is usually resolved in the following ways:\n\n* Often, the volume or surface on which the force acts is relatively small compared to the size of the body, so that it can be approximated by a point. It is usually not difficult to determine whether the error caused by such approximation is acceptable.\n* If it is not acceptable (obviously e.g. in the case of gravitational force), such \"volume/surface\" force should be described as a system of forces (components), each acting on a single particle, and then the calculation should be done for each of them separately. Such a calculation is typically simplified by the use of differential elements of the body volume/surface, and the integral calculus. In a number of cases, though, it can be shown that such a system of forces may be replaced by a single point force without the actual calculation (as in the case of uniform gravitational force).\n\nIn any case, the analysis of the rigid body motion begins with the point force model. And when a force acting on a body is shown graphically, the oriented line segment representing the force is usually drawn so as to \"begin\" (or \"end\") at the application point.\n\n===Rigid bodies===\n[[File:Free body acceleration.JPG|thumb|300px|How a force accelerates a body.]]\nIn the example shown in the diagram opposite, a single force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F </math> acts at the application point '''H''' on a free rigid body. The body has the mass <math>\\scriptstyle m </math> and its center of mass is the point '''C'''. In the constant mass approximation, the force causes changes in the body motion described by the following expressions:\n\n: <math> \\vec a = {\\vec F \\over m} </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the center of mass acceleration; and\n\n: <math> \\vec \\alpha = {\\vec \\tau \\over I} </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the [[angular acceleration]] of the body.\n\nIn the second expression, <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec \\tau </math> is the [[torque]] or moment of force, whereas <math>\\scriptstyle I </math> is the [[moment of inertia]] of the body. A torque caused by a force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F </math> is a vector quantity defined with respect to some reference point:\n\n:<math> \\vec \\tau = \\vec r \\times \\vec F </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the torque vector, and\n\n:<math> \\ \\tau = Fk </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the amount of torque.\n\nThe vector <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r </math> is the [[position vector]] of the force application point, and in this example it is drawn from the center of mass as the reference point of (see diagram). The straight line segment <math>\\scriptstyle k </math> is the lever arm of the force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F </math> with respect to the center of mass. As the illustration suggests, the torque does not change (the same lever arm) if the application point is moved along the line of the application of the force (dotted black line). More formally, this follows from the properties of the vector product, and shows that rotational effect of the force depends only on the position of its line of application, and not on the particular choice of the point of application along that line.\n\nThe torque vector is perpendicular to the plane defined by the force and the vector <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r </math>, and in this example it is directed towards the observer; the angular acceleration vector has the same direction. The [[right hand rule]] relates this direction to the clockwise or counter-clockwise rotation in the plane of the drawing.\n\nThe moment of inertia <math>\\scriptstyle I </math> is calculated with respect to the axis through the center of mass that is parallel with the torque. If the body shown in the illustration is a homogeneous disc, this moment of inertia is <math>\\scriptstyle I=m r^2 /2 </math> . If the disc has the mass 0,5&nbsp;kg and the radius 0,8 m, the moment of inertia is 0,16 kgm<sup>2</sup>. If the amount of force is 2 N, and the lever arm 0,6 m, the amount of torque is 1,2 Nm. At the instant shown, the force gives to the disc the angular acceleration \u03b1 = {{math|''\u03c4''}}/I = 7,5 rad/s<sup>2</sup>, and to its center of mass it gives the linear acceleration a&nbsp;= F/m&nbsp;= 4&nbsp;m/s<sup>2</sup>.\n\n== Resultant force ==\n[[File:Rezultanta.JPG|thumb|500px|Graphical placing of the resultant force.]]\n\n[[Resultant force]] and torque replaces the effects of a system of forces acting on the movement of a rigid body.  An interesting special case is a torque-free resultant, which can be found as follows:\n# Vector addition is used to find the net force;\n# Use the equation to determine the point of application with zero torque:\n:<math> \\vec r \\times \\vec F_\\mathrm{R} = \\sum_{i=1}^N ( \\vec r_i \\times \\vec F_i ) </math>\nwhere <math> \\vec F_\\mathrm{R} </math> is the net force, <math> \\vec r</math> locates its application point, and individual forces are <math> \\vec F_i </math> with application points <math> \\vec r_i </math>.  It may be that there is no point of application that yields a torque-free resultant.\n<!----\n  This paragraph confuse[s?] a resultant force and torque with a torque-free resultant:\n\nThe above equation may have no solution for <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r</math>. In that case, there is no resultant force, i.e. no single force can replace all actual forces regarding both linear and angular acceleration of the body. And even when <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r</math> can be calculated, it is not unique, because the point of application can move along the line of application without affecting the torque.\n ---->\n\nThe diagram opposite illustrates simple graphical methods for finding the line of application of the resultant force of simple planar systems:\n# Lines of application of the actual forces <math>\\vec{F}_{1}</math> and <math>\\vec{F}_{2}</math> on the leftmost illustration intersect. After vector addition is performed \"at the location of <math> \\vec{F}_{1}</math>\", the net force obtained is translated so that its line of application passes through the common intersection point. With respect to that point all torques are zero, so the torque of the resultant force <math>\\vec{F}_\\mathrm{R}</math> is equal to the sum of the torques of the actual forces.\n# The illustration in the middle of the diagram shows two parallel actual forces. After vector addition \"at the location of <math>\\vec{F}_{2}</math>\", the net force is translated to the appropriate line of application, where it becomes the resultant force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_\\mathrm{R}</math>. The procedure is based on decomposition of all forces into components for which the lines of application (pale dotted lines) intersect at one point (the so-called pole, arbitrarily set at the right side of the illustration). Then the arguments from the previous case are applied to the forces and their components to demonstrate the torque relationships.\n# The rightmost illustration shows a [[couple (mechanics)|couple]], two equal but opposite forces for which the amount of the net force is zero, but they produce the net torque <math> \\scriptstyle \\tau = Fd </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;where <math> \\scriptstyle \\ d </math>&nbsp; is the distance between their lines of application. Since there is no resultant force, this torque can be [is?] described as \"pure\" torque.\n\n== Usage ==\n[[File:Non-parallel net force.svg|thumb|279px|Vector diagram for addition of non-parallel forces.]]\n\nIn general, a system of forces acting on a rigid body can always be replaced by one force plus one pure (see previous section) torque. The force is the net force, but to calculate the additional torque, the net force must be assigned the line of action. The line of action can be selected arbitrarily, but the additional pure torque depends on this choice. In a special case, it is possible to find such line of action that this additional torque is zero.\n\nThe [[resultant force]] and torque can be determined for any configuration of forces.  However, an interesting special case is a torque-free resultant. This is useful, both conceptually and practically, because the body moves without rotating as if it was a particle.\n<!----\n  These paragraphs [This paragraph?] seems to be redundant:\n\nWhen the system of forces can be replaced by a resultant force, this can simplify practical calculations (e.g. in many planar systems, or using the center of gravity in homogenous field, etc.). On the conceptual level, definition of the resultant force underlines the fact that the net force does not fully replace the system of forces (so, for example, the [[work physics|work]] of the net force cannot replace the net work in the case of an extended rigid body, e.g. in the work-energy theorem etc.). And the concept is also useful for a full understanding of a more general approach.\n\n[[File:Parallel net force.svg|thumb|185px|Vector diagram for addition of parallel forces.]]\n ---->\n\nSome authors do not distinguish the resultant force from the net force and use the terms as [[synonym]]s.<ref>Resnick, Robert and Halliday, David (1966), Physics, (Vol I and II, Combined edition), Wiley International Edition, Library of Congress Catalog Card No. 66-11527</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Screw theory]]\n* [[Center of mass]]\n* [[Centers of gravity in non-uniform fields]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Force]]\n[[Category:Dynamics (mechanics)]]\n", "text_old": "Net force is the [[vector sum]] of forces acting on a particle or body. The net force is a single force that replaces the effect of the original forces on the particle's motion. It gives the particle the same [[acceleration]] as all those actual forces together as described by the [[Newton's laws of motion|Newton's second law of motion]].\n\nIn [[physics]], it is possible to determine the torque associated with the point of application of a net force so that it maintains the movement of jets of the object under the original system of forces. Its associated torque, the net force, becomes the ''[[resultant force]]'' and has the same effect on the [[rotation]]al motion of the object as all actual forces taken together.<ref>Symon, Keith R. (1964), Mechanics, Addison-Wesley, {{LCCN|605164}}</ref>  It is possible for a system of forces to define a torque-free resultant force. In this case, the net force, when applied at the proper line of action, has the same effect on the body as all of the forces at their points of application. It is not always possible to find a torque-free resultant force.\n<!----\n  This discussion of forces on a particle and rigid body is confusing:\n\nA acting on an object may cause changes in the motion or in the shape (configuration) of the object. When two or more forces are acting on an object, the concepts of net force and resultant force are intended to simplify description of their effect on its motion.\n\nIf the forces are acting on a [[Part]] (the size of the object is so Tinsie Winnsie that it can be approximated by a point), they can only change its [[velocity]]. In that case, there is no difference between the net force and the resultant force because no rotation is associated with such objects.\n\nIf the object is an extended but [[rigid body]] (no change in shape), the forces can change its velocity (i.e. the velocity of its [[center of mass]], usually called its linear velocity) as well as its [[angular velocity]]. In that case, it may be useful to distinguish the resultant force from the net force. And even in the case of non-rigid objects (deformable bodies or systems), the concepts of net and resultant force are equally applicable to description of their overall motion.\n\nSome authors use \"resultant force\" and \"net force\" as synonyms, even when the forces act on extended bodies. However, this is generally not the case (see the note on usage at the end of the article) in [[mechanics]] and in those technical applications where full understanding and actual calculations of the rotating body [[dynamics (mechanics)|dynamics]] (or even of the [[static equilibrium]]) are required.\n ---->\n\n== Total force ==\n\n[[File:Addition of forces.JPG|thumb|350px|A<!--?: nother--> diagrammatic method for the addition of forces.]]\n\nForce is a [[Euclidean vector|vector]] quantity, which means that it has a magnitude and a direction, and it is usually denoted using boldface such as '''F''' or by using an arrow over the symbol, such as <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F</math>. \n\nGraphically, a force is represented as a line segment from its point of application ''A'' to a point ''B'', which defines its direction and magnitude.  The length of the segment ''AB'' represents the magnitude of the force.\n\n[[Vector calculus]] was developed in the late 1800s and early 1900s. The [[parallelogram rule]] used for the addition of forces, however, dates from antiquity and is noted explicitly by Galileo and Newton.<ref>Michael J. Crowe (1967). ''A History of Vector Analysis : The Evolution of the Idea of a Vectorial System''. Dover Publications (reprint edition; {{ISBN|0-486-67910-1}}).</ref> \n\nThe diagram shows the addition of the forces <math>\\scriptstyle  \\vec{F}_{1}</math> and <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{2}</math>. The sum <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F</math> of the two forces is drawn as the diagonal of a parallelogram defined by the two forces. \n<!----\n  This \"intuitive\" description is not intuitive:\n\nThis can be grasped intuitively: if the total force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F</math> should describe the joint effect of the two forces on a particle (which is the intrinsic meaning of addition), its direction should be closer to the direction of the stronger force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{2}</math>, and its amount should be greater than the amount of <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{2}</math> because <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_{1}</math> also helps in pulling the particle in that  \"general\" direction (for the forces shown in the diagram). \n\nIndependent of this approximate intuitive judgment, the rule of parallelogram gives the exact result, which is easily verified by measuring the effects of the forces. The result can be approximately evaluated from the diagram or, based on the diagram, precisely calculated using elementary [[trigonometry]].\n ----><!----\n  This is not an alternative to the parallelogram rule, it -is- the parallelogram rule:\n\nInstead of using the parallelogram rule, the same result can be obtained by a simpler procedure (shown on the right side of the diagram). The line segments representing the original forces can be translated (in any order) so that one begins where the other ends. The same result for the vector sum is the line drawn from the beginning of the first segment to the end of the second&nbsp;\u2013 or to the end of the last one&nbsp;\u2013 which enables simple addition of more than two vectors. At the bottom of the diagram, this procedure is applied to the addition of two parallel and antiparallel forces, leading to the intuitively expected result: for parallel forces the amounts add up, whereas for the forces in opposite directions (antiparallel) the amount of the smaller force is subtracted from the bigger one.\n ---->\n\nForces applied to an extended body can have different points of application.  Forces are bound vectors and can be added only if they are applied at the same point.  The net force obtained from all the forces acting on a body  do not preserve its motion unless applied at the same point, and with the appropriate torque associated with the new point of application determined.  The net force on a body applied at a single point with the appropriate torque is known as the [[resultant force]] and torque.\n\n== Parallelogram rule for the addition of forces ==\n[[File:Parallelogram1.svg|right|Parallelogram ABCD]]\n\nA force is known as a bound vector\u2014which means it has a direction and magnitude and a point of application.  A convenient way to define a force is by a line segment from a point ''A'' to a point ''B''.  If we denote the coordinates of these points as '''A'''=(A<sub>x</sub>, A<sub>y</sub>, A<sub>z</sub>) and  '''B'''=(B<sub>x</sub>, B<sub>y</sub>, B<sub>z</sub>), then the force vector applied at ''A'' is given by\n: <math> \\mathbf{F}= \\mathbf{B}-\\mathbf{A} = (B_x-A_x, B_y-A_y, B_z-A_z). </math>\nThe length of the vector '''B'''-'''A''' defines the magnitude of '''F''' and is given by\n: <math> |\\mathbf{F}| = \\sqrt{(B_x-A_x)^2+(B_y-A_y)^2+(B_z-A_z)^2}. </math>\n\nThe sum of two forces '''F'''<sub>1</sub> and  '''F'''<sub>2</sub> applied at ''A'' can be computed from the sum of the segments that define them.  Let '''F'''<sub>1</sub>='''B'''-'''A''' and '''F'''<sub>2</sub>='''D'''-'''A''', then the sum of these two vectors is\n: <math> \\mathbf{F}=\\mathbf{F}_1+\\mathbf{F}_2 = \\mathbf{B}-\\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{D}-\\mathbf{A},</math>\nwhich can be written as\n: <math> \\mathbf{F}=\\mathbf{F}_1+\\mathbf{F}_2 = 2(\\frac{\\mathbf{B}+\\mathbf{D}}{2}-\\mathbf{A})=2(\\mathbf{E}-\\mathbf{A}),</math>\nwhere '''E''' is the midpoint of the segment '''BD''' that joins the points ''B'' and ''D''.  \n\nThus, the sum of the forces '''F'''<sub>1</sub> and '''F'''<sub>2</sub> is twice the segment joining ''A'' to the midpoint ''E'' of the segment joining the endpoints ''B'' and ''D'' of the two forces.  The doubling of this length is easily achieved by defining a segments '''BC''' and '''DC''' parallel to '''AD''' and '''AB''', respectively, to complete the parallelogram ''ABCD''.  The diagonal '''AC''' of this parallelogram is the sum of the two force vectors.  This is known as the parallelogram rule for the addition of forces.\n\n== Translation and rotation due to a force ==\n\n===Point forces===\nWhen a force acts on a particle, it is applied to a single point (the particle volume is negligible): this is a point force and the particle is its application point. But an external force on an extended body (object) can be applied to a number of its constituent particles, i.e. can be \"spread\" over some volume or surface of the body. However, determining its rotational effect on the body requires that we specify its point of application (actually, the line of application, as explained below). The problem is usually resolved in the following ways:\n\n* Often, the volume or surface on which the force acts is relatively small compared to the size of the body, so that it can be approximated by a point. It is usually not difficult to determine whether the error caused by such approximation is acceptable.\n* If it is not acceptable (obviously e.g. in the case of gravitational force), such \"volume/surface\" force should be described as a system of forces (components), each acting on a single particle, and then the calculation should be done for each of them separately. Such a calculation is typically simplified by the use of differential elements of the body volume/surface, and the integral calculus. In a number of cases, though, it can be shown that such a system of forces may be replaced by a single point force without the actual calculation (as in the case of uniform gravitational force).\n\nIn any case, the analysis of the rigid body motion begins with the point force model. And when a force acting on a body is shown graphically, the oriented line segment representing the force is usually drawn so as to \"begin\" (or \"end\") at the application point.\n\n===Rigid bodies===\n[[File:Free body acceleration.JPG|thumb|300px|How a force accelerates a body.]]\nIn the example shown in the diagram opposite, a single force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F </math> acts at the application point '''H''' on a free rigid body. The body has the mass <math>\\scriptstyle m </math> and its center of mass is the point '''C'''. In the constant mass approximation, the force causes changes in the body motion described by the following expressions:\n\n: <math> \\vec a = {\\vec F \\over m} </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the center of mass acceleration; and\n\n: <math> \\vec \\alpha = {\\vec \\tau \\over I} </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the [[angular acceleration]] of the body.\n\nIn the second expression, <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec \\tau </math> is the [[torque]] or moment of force, whereas <math>\\scriptstyle I </math> is the [[moment of inertia]] of the body. A torque caused by a force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F </math> is a vector quantity defined with respect to some reference point:\n\n:<math> \\vec \\tau = \\vec r \\times \\vec F </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the torque vector, and\n\n:<math> \\ \\tau = Fk </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;is the amount of torque.\n\nThe vector <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r </math> is the [[position vector]] of the force application point, and in this example it is drawn from the center of mass as the reference point of (see diagram). The straight line segment <math>\\scriptstyle k </math> is the lever arm of the force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec F </math> with respect to the center of mass. As the illustration suggests, the torque does not change (the same lever arm) if the application point is moved along the line of the application of the force (dotted black line). More formally, this follows from the properties of the vector product, and shows that rotational effect of the force depends only on the position of its line of application, and not on the particular choice of the point of application along that line.\n\nThe torque vector is perpendicular to the plane defined by the force and the vector <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r </math>, and in this example it is directed towards the observer; the angular acceleration vector has the same direction. The [[right hand rule]] relates this direction to the clockwise or counter-clockwise rotation in the plane of the drawing.\n\nThe moment of inertia <math>\\scriptstyle I </math> is calculated with respect to the axis through the center of mass that is parallel with the torque. If the body shown in the illustration is a homogeneous disc, this moment of inertia is <math>\\scriptstyle I=m r^2 /2 </math> . If the disc has the mass 0,5&nbsp;kg and the radius 0,8 m, the moment of inertia is 0,16 kgm<sup>2</sup>. If the amount of force is 2 N, and the lever arm 0,6 m, the amount of torque is 1,2 Nm. At the instant shown, the force gives to the disc the angular acceleration \u03b1 = {{math|''\u03c4''}}/I = 7,5 rad/s<sup>2</sup>, and to its center of mass it gives the linear acceleration a&nbsp;= F/m&nbsp;= 4&nbsp;m/s<sup>2</sup>.\n\n== Resultant force ==\n[[File:Rezultanta.JPG|thumb|500px|Graphical placing of the resultant force.]]\n\n[[Resultant force]] and torque replaces the effects of a system of forces acting on the movement of a rigid body.  An interesting special case is a torque-free resultant, which can be found as follows:\n# Vector addition is used to find the net force;\n# Use the equation to determine the point of application with zero torque:\n:<math> \\vec r \\times \\vec F_\\mathrm{R} = \\sum_{i=1}^N ( \\vec r_i \\times \\vec F_i ) </math>\nwhere <math> \\vec F_\\mathrm{R} </math> is the net force, <math> \\vec r</math> locates its application point, and individual forces are <math> \\vec F_i </math> with application points <math> \\vec r_i </math>.  It may be that there is no point of application that yields a torque-free resultant.\n<!----\n  This paragraph confuse[s?] a resultant force and torque with a torque-free resultant:\n\nThe above equation may have no solution for <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r</math>. In that case, there is no resultant force, i.e. no single force can replace all actual forces regarding both linear and angular acceleration of the body. And even when <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec r</math> can be calculated, it is not unique, because the point of application can move along the line of application without affecting the torque.\n ---->\n\nThe diagram opposite illustrates simple graphical methods for finding the line of application of the resultant force of simple planar systems:\n# Lines of application of the actual forces <math>\\vec{F}_{1}</math> and <math>\\vec{F}_{2}</math> on the leftmost illustration intersect. After vector addition is performed \"at the location of <math> \\vec{F}_{1}</math>\", the net force obtained is translated so that its line of application passes through the common intersection point. With respect to that point all torques are zero, so the torque of the resultant force <math>\\vec{F}_\\mathrm{R}</math> is equal to the sum of the torques of the actual forces.\n# The illustration in the middle of the diagram shows two parallel actual forces. After vector addition \"at the location of <math>\\vec{F}_{2}</math>\", the net force is translated to the appropriate line of application, where it becomes the resultant force <math>\\scriptstyle \\vec{F}_\\mathrm{R}</math>. The procedure is based on decomposition of all forces into components for which the lines of application (pale dotted lines) intersect at one point (the so-called pole, arbitrarily set at the right side of the illustration). Then the arguments from the previous case are applied to the forces and their components to demonstrate the torque relationships.\n# The rightmost illustration shows a [[couple (mechanics)|couple]], two equal but opposite forces for which the amount of the net force is zero, but they produce the net torque <math> \\scriptstyle \\tau = Fd </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;where <math> \\scriptstyle \\ d </math>&nbsp; is the distance between their lines of application. Since there is no resultant force, this torque can be [is?] described as \"pure\" torque.\n\n== Usage ==\n[[File:Non-parallel net force.svg|thumb|279px|Vector diagram for addition of non-parallel forces.]]\n\nIn general, a system of forces acting on a rigid body can always be replaced by one force plus one pure (see previous section) torque. The force is the net force, but to calculate the additional torque, the net force must be assigned the line of action. The line of action can be selected arbitrarily, but the additional pure torque depends on this choice. In a special case, it is possible to find such line of action that this additional torque is zero.\n\nThe [[resultant force]] and torque can be determined for any configuration of forces.  However, an interesting special case is a torque-free resultant. This is useful, both conceptually and practically, because the body moves without rotating as if it was a particle.\n<!----\n  These paragraphs [This paragraph?] seems to be redundant:\n\nWhen the system of forces can be replaced by a resultant force, this can simplify practical calculations (e.g. in many planar systems, or using the center of gravity in homogenous field, etc.). On the conceptual level, definition of the resultant force underlines the fact that the net force does not fully replace the system of forces (so, for example, the [[work physics|work]] of the net force cannot replace the net work in the case of an extended rigid body, e.g. in the work-energy theorem etc.). And the concept is also useful for a full understanding of a more general approach.\n\n[[File:Parallel net force.svg|thumb|185px|Vector diagram for addition of parallel forces.]]\n ---->\n\nSome authors do not distinguish the resultant force from the net force and use the terms as [[synonym]]s.<ref>Resnick, Robert and Halliday, David (1966), Physics, (Vol I and II, Combined edition), Wiley International Edition, Library of Congress Catalog Card No. 66-11527</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Screw theory]]\n* [[Center of mass]]\n* [[Centers of gravity in non-uniform fields]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Force]]\n[[Category:Dynamics (mechanics)]]\n", "name_user": "2601:3c7:8300:6830:b59e:4f51:dc29:ee4c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Net_force"}
{"title_page": "Loop Service", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = A B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n{{endplainlist}}\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|4.4|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|4.4|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side, between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]]. This line was one of many proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association for the east side.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane deck rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weilder avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weilder alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the streetcar along this new bridge proposal instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=City of Portland Office of Transportation |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a three-phased eastside loop project that ran from the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\n===Funding and construction===\n[[File:Broadway-Bridge-Streetcar-Construction.jpg|thumb|right|The Broadway Bridge under construction in 2010]]\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006;<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> this was followed by an approval from the Portland City Council in September 2007.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The estimated total cost of the project was $147{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|147000000|2009}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), just over half of which would be paid for with federal funds. This budget was adjusted to $148.3{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148300000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars) in 2012, including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>  This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was both the largest and the final component of the financing plan, and meant the project could proceed with construction. The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the financing plan.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2009, local manufacturer [[United Streetcar]] delivered its first streetcar prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension,<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> which it reduced to five in 2011 after production glitches raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's construction manager and general contractor. Crews completed track-laying in three- to four-block segments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to cars, bicycles, and pedestrians from July 19 to September 3, 2010 to make way for track installation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In August 2010, sewer rehabilitation work caused sewage to leak into the Willamette River.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/08/09/streetcar-construction-springs-sewage-leak/ |last=Weinstein |first=Nathalie |title=Streetcar construction springs sewage leak |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=August 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\n\nThe Central Loop Line began service on September 22, 2012, running from Southwest Market Street to the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI) via the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The {{convert|3.35|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} line cost $148.3 million to construct and opened five months late,<ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> with 18-minute frequencies instead of the planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by [[TriMet]] and the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]] as well as delays in streetcar delivery from [[United Streetcar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces \u2018Central Loop\u2019 Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, a new temporary schedule eliminated the CL Line in favor of the A Loop and B Loop, extended from SW 10th and Market along the NS Line south to SW Moody Avenue & SW Meade Street in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]]. Streetcars began operating across the new [[Tilikum Crossing]] transit bridge on that date, but not carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional phase which was referred to as \"pre-revenue service\".<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015, when the opening of the Tilikum Crossing to the public permitted streetcars to begin carrying passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/><ref name=\"PS-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|B-Loop streetcar crossing the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in 2016]]\n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, of which 24 are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at 10 stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"Schedule\">{{cite web |date=August 30, 2015 |title=Streetcar Schedule |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = A B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n{{endplainlist}}\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|4.4|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|4.4|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side, between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]]. This line was one of many proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association for the east side.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane deck rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weilder avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weilder alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the streetcar along this new bridge instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=City of Portland Office of Transportation |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a three-phased eastside loop project that ran from the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\n===Funding and construction===\n[[File:Broadway-Bridge-Streetcar-Construction.jpg|thumb|right|The Broadway Bridge under construction in 2010]]\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006;<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> this was followed by an approval from the Portland City Council in September 2007.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The estimated total cost of the project was $147{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|147000000|2009}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), just over half of which would be paid for with federal funds. This budget was adjusted to $148.3{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148300000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars) in 2012, including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>  This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was both the largest and the final component of the financing plan, and meant the project could proceed with construction. The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the financing plan.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2009, local manufacturer [[United Streetcar]] delivered its first streetcar prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension,<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> which it reduced to five in 2011 after production glitches raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's construction manager and general contractor. Crews completed track-laying in three- to four-block segments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to cars, bicycles, and pedestrians from July 19 to September 3, 2010 to make way for track installation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In August 2010, sewer rehabilitation work caused sewage to leak into the Willamette River.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/08/09/streetcar-construction-springs-sewage-leak/ |last=Weinstein |first=Nathalie |title=Streetcar construction springs sewage leak |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=August 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\n\nThe Central Loop Line began service on September 22, 2012, running from Southwest Market Street to the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI) via the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The {{convert|3.35|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} line cost $148.3 million to construct and opened five months late,<ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> with 18-minute frequencies instead of the planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by [[TriMet]] and the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]] as well as delays in streetcar delivery from [[United Streetcar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces \u2018Central Loop\u2019 Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, a new temporary schedule eliminated the CL Line in favor of the A Loop and B Loop, extended from SW 10th and Market along the NS Line south to SW Moody Avenue & SW Meade Street in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]]. Streetcars began operating across the new [[Tilikum Crossing]] transit bridge on that date, but not carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional phase which was referred to as \"pre-revenue service\".<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015, when the opening of the Tilikum Crossing to the public permitted streetcars to begin carrying passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/><ref name=\"PS-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|B-Loop streetcar crossing the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in 2016]]\n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, of which 24 are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at 10 stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\